'''Middle child syndrome''' is the feeling of exclusion by [[birth order|middle children]].<ref name="middle gen">{{cite book|last1=Bracy|first1=Earl E.|last2=Alexander|first2=Tyesha|author1=|title=The Middle Generation Syndrome: (A Throw Away Society)|date=2013|publisher=Dorrance Publishing|isbn=978-1-4809-0008-0|pages=145-146|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qMjjBtYoNn0C&pg=PA46&dq=middle+child+syndrome&hl=en&sa=X&ei=A3l4VK_fKdbZsAT5p4D4Cw&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=middle%20child%20syndrome&f=false}}</ref> This effect occurs because the first child is more prone to receiving privileges and responsibilities (by virtue of being the oldest), while the youngest in the family is more likely to receive indulgences. The second child (or middle child) no longer has their status as the baby and is left with no clear role in the family,<ref name="gifted children">{{cite book|last1=Gore|first1=Janet L.|last2=Amend|first2=Edward R.|title=A Parent's Guide to Gifted Children|publisher=Great Potential Press|isbn=0-910707-52-9|pages=197-198|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZyVXGPPj9rgC&pg=PA198&dq=middle+child+syndrome&hl=en&sa=X&ei=A3l4VK_fKdbZsAT5p4D4Cw&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=middle%20child%20syndrome&f=false}}</ref> or a feeling of being "left out".<ref name="getting started">{{cite book|last1=Kotin|first1=Joel|title=Getting Started: An Introduction to Dynamic Psychotherapy|date=1995|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers, Inc.|isbn=1-56821-451-0|page=46|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qMjjBtYoNn0C&pg=PA46&dq=middle+child+syndrome&hl=en&sa=X&ei=A3l4VK_fKdbZsAT5p4D4Cw&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=middle%20child%20syndrome&f=false}}{{cite book|last1=Guarendi|first1=Raymond N.|title=You're a Better Parent Than You Think!: A Guide to Common-Sense Parenting|date=1985|publisher=Prentice Hall Press|isbn=0-671-76595-7|page=83|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7DxlzF5Rdb8C&pg=PA83&dq=middle+child+syndrome&hl=en&sa=X&ei=A3l4VK_fKdbZsAT5p4D4Cw&ved=0CEgQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=middle%20child%20syndrome&f=false}}</ref>
