{{Infobox ethnic group | group = Swiss Tibetan | image = Die Schweiz für Tibet - Tibet für die Welt - GSTF Solidaritätskundgebung am 10 April 2010 in Zürich IMG 5703.JPG | population = 4,000+<ref name = "tibetpost" /> | popplace = [[Zurich]], [[Geneva]] | langs = [[Tibetic languages|Tibetan]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[German language|German]], [[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[English language|English]] | rels = [[Buddhism]] | related = [[Tibetan people|Tibetan]]s }} '''Tibetans have been in Switzerland''' since the 1960s, when the [[Swiss Red Cross]] helped resettle 300 Tibetans in [[Switzerland]]. In addition, approximately 150 Tibetan [[orphans]] were adopted by Swiss families. A number of Tibetans settled in the mountains of the [[Swiss Alps]], because of its [[Tibetan Plateau|homelike terrain]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Buchser | first = Corine | title = Why the Swiss accepted Tibetans with open arms | newspaper = swissinfo.ch | location = Berne | pages = | language = | publisher = Swiss Broadcasting Corporation | date = Apr 9, 2010 | url = http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/politics/Why_the_Swiss_accepted_Tibetans_with_open_arms.html?cid=8643062 | accessdate = July 22, 2011}}</ref> The Tibetan children had some difficulty in school, due to the massive language barrier between German and Tibetan. But soon enough, the Tibetans were able to gain enough fluency in [[German language|German]], and were able to sit in the same class as regular Swiss children.<ref name = "tibetsun" /> Many of these Tibetan children would assimilate into the Swiss society, and would become "culturally confused".<ref>{{Cite book | last = Hess | first = Julia Meredith | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Immigrant ambassadors: citizenship and belonging in the Tibetan diaspora | publisher = Stanford University Press | year = 2009 | location = Stanford, CA | page = 98 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=08KU9bTxdRAC&pg=PA98&lpg=PA98&dq=switzerland+tibetans+immigrants&source=bl&ots=pwvegpNaO3&sig=Qi46sqzBScJgFyW_kmaRlG0YA8E&hl=en&ei=BT_XTbWMMca_gQe7sZ1Y&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CEEQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=switzerland%20tibetans%20immigrants&f=false | isbn = 978-0-8047-6017-1}}</ref> Some Swiss people even learned to speak in some Tibetan.<ref name = "tibetsun" >{{Cite news | title = Tibetans in Switzerland | newspaper = The Observer | location = London | publisher = Tibet Sun | date = 27 June 1964 | url = http://www.tibetsun.com/archive/1964/06/27/tibetans-in-switzerland/ | accessdate = July 22, 2011}}</ref>
With over 4000 residing in the country, [[Tibetan people|Tibetan]]s make up the second largest [[Asian people|Asian]] [[immigrant]] group in Switzerland, right behind [[Filipinos in Switzerland|Filipinos]].<ref name = "tibetpost" >{{Cite news | last = Dhardowa | first = YC | title = Tibet PM Thanks Swiss for 50 years of Refugee Shelter | newspaper = The Tibet Post International | location = | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = Feb 2011 | url = http://www.thetibetpost.com/en/news/international/1481-tibet-pm-thanks-swiss-for-50-years-of-refugee-shelter | accessdate = July 22, 2011}}</ref>
